column31: I was reading some posts for and against reopening the country. One was talking about being selfish and it got me to thinking. — There are those wanting to reopen yet they’re being classified as selfish. And then there are those that rely on all kinds of people to supply them while they cower in fear at home. Isn’t that being selfish too? — You expect your garbage to be picked up, you expect the grocery store to be open so you can get milk, you expect truck drivers to continue to supply the stores, you expect farmers, meatpackers, fruit and vegetable pickers to keep food in that very grocery store. — You expect Amazon to continue to ship all the things you are ordering while you sit at home shopping. You expect the delivery driver to leave it on your doorstep. You expect your phone to work, your power to stay on, and your mail to show up rain, sleet, or shine. And most important, you expect the doctors and nurses to be there if you need them although many of them across the country have been furloughed because their units and services have been shut down because many hospitals are empty. — The whole premise of shelter in place is based on the arrogant idea that others must risk their health so you can protect yours. There is nothing virtuous about ignoring the largely invisible army required to allow people to shelter in place. — Written by Katherine Bennett Amirteymour — #repost @meet.the.hamptons Image source @pinterest #quarantine #reopenamerica #covid_19 #publichealth #humanrights #protectallpeople #freedom

column31: Why we're so passionate about medical freedom.... Today at Ohio Governor DeWine's daily briefly, a reporter asked a question that went like this: "So the anti-mask people have more of a voice than the pro-mask people?" He said more than that, but was clearly irritated by the position that masks are 'strongly recommended' but not 'required.' Listen. We see this same type of query in regards to vaccines. "So the anti-vax crowd gets more of a voice than the pro-vax crowd?" Well, if you must draw it as us vs. them, then yes. They do. Here's why. The PRO crowd in both cases is not "I think this is a good idea and I want to encourage people to do it." That voice can and should be heard everywhere. They have every right to stand up for what they believe in, and share that information, and encourage others to do the same. Rather, the PRO crowd is "I want *every* person to do this and I think it shouldn't be optional." They want to *force* everyone into a specific decision. No exceptions. Meanwhile, the ANTI crowd is saying, "I don't want to take away anyone else's choice, but I don't want to do that myself." These two positions are necessarily in complete opposition. One is that everyone must do something without any option; the other is that each person gets to make their own choice. If even one person gets to say "no," then the PRO crowd has not gotten their way. They have built people into enemies who did not desire to be their enemies. They have "othered" people based on their personal decision. They are not *asking* them to consider a decision; they are insisting and are ready to strong-arm them and take away their right choose. Consider how irrational that actually is. This is why the "we're in it together" and "I'm making decisions for YOU" is very damaging. We may face the same situation, but we do not have the same circumstances, personality, risk factors, ideas, or preferences. We are not the same. There is room for disagreements and different decisions. When one person believes that there is one right way to go about things, they believe in conformity. They believe that they are upholding a social contract, and others who make different decisions are not. They come to see those "others" as the enemy. They believe they made a good decision that benefits YOU, yet you won't do the same for them? You are bad. You are evil. Like we said, damaging. Sometimes people will make decisions that are bad for others. That's part of being in society. We do not get to control others. But we can still be good humans, and we can still be in community, as long as we respect one another's boundaries. Where does that leave us on mask-wearing? If you will be around someone or in someone's home and you know they are worried, ask if they would prefer you wear a mask in their space. (Unless you truly cannot.) Offer to wash your hands. Choose to stay away if they prefer you to. In public spaces, do what you feel is right. Mostly we are not in close contact with others anyway and that is most important. Look at the facts about masks and understand the pros and cons of different types and make a thoughtful decision. Stay home if you are sick. You can be considerate of others, and still set your own boundaries. Find that sweet spot. It will look a bit different for each person. Respect where others fall, even if it's not what you would do or prefer. Don't use manipulative language to get others to do things your way. Hear others and their situations and their ideas. Can we be good humans, and truly respect each other? We'd love to see that.

column31: This is why we remain concerned about the government's response to the coronavirus threat. In Ohio, the governor has been making decisions (alongside the leader of the Health Department, who has "final authority" on all pandemic-related matters) based on models of what things might look like. The last time they shared these models publicly was April 4, in order to encourage us that all of the closures were the "right thing." That was the last time the models were remotely close to accurate. The first graph shows a green line, which is the model that they used to describe what would happen "if we did nothing." It shows a very rapid rise in cases, peaking at 62,000 new cases per day on March 22. The red line represents what they thought they could achieve with their closures and social distancing measures, which is a 6-fold drop in the peak cases per day, and a shift back about a month. That is, specifically, 10,000 new cases per day, peaking on Apr. 25. The blue line is REALITY. The blue line represents a 20-fold drop from the red line, and a 124-fold drop from the green line. The "peak" was somewhere around the beginning of April, but the data was skewed a couple different times. On April 10, they started including "probable" cases, so the slight downward trend came back up. Then, on April 18 - 20, they mass-tested a few prisons and picked up a bunch of asymptomatic cases that wouldn't have met "testing criteria" or been included typically (that's the bump you see in the line). So we need to ask ourselves. Based on the data of what actually happened...were their models EVER realistic? If "social distancing" was expected to produce a 6-fold reduction in the peak cases, and our peak was actually around 500 cases per day, then the do-nothing peak would have been around 3000 cases per day. This is still 3x better than the "best case scenario" they presented to us. And that's IF social distancing actually had that great an impact. Based on the numbers we've seen out of a few areas where much milder measures were put in place, and the few large ships...we don't think so. We were told that this was necessary so that the medical system wouldn't be overwhelmed. Ohio has 34,000 hospital beds and 2500 of those are ICU. In the past 7 weeks, 3115 people were hospitalized and 938 were in the ICU. That is not "all at once." Had the peak been 6x times worse, we would have needed 18,690 hospital beds (about half the total available) and 5,628 ICU beds. Since this is over a long span of time, it's likely that we would have had plenty of resources available. The leaders need to be called to account for this. The effects of the shut down are devastating and will be long-lasting. Obviously they didn't have all the data up front, no one did, but they made decisions quickly and out of fear. And refused to adjust those decisions as new data came out. They worked off faulty models for way too long. How do you feel about this?

column31: There isn’t just one threat in our environment…. We tend to think that cancer is happening more because we’re living longer, or only affects the elderly, but the truth is, cancer is increasing for all age groups, including infants, children and young adults. In 2020, it was estimated there will be 89,000 new cases of cancer diagnosed, and 9,270 cancer deaths in adolescents and young adults ages 15-38 years in the US, and 11,050 children under 15 will be diagnosed with cancer. Millennials (born between 1981-1996) are five times as likely as baby boomers to develop cancer of the kidneys, and at an increased risk for gastrointestinal cancer, leukemia, colorectal, endometrial, gallbladder, pancreatic, and multiple myeloma. Only about 5-10 percent of cancers are considered inherited genetic mutations. The remaining majority of cancers are environmental or epigenetic, which has to do with how our genes are expressed and regulated. "In-vitro, animal, and human investigations have identified several classes of environmental chemicals that modify epigenetic marks, including metals (cadmium, arsenic, nickel, chromium, methylmercury), peroxisome proliferators (trichloroethylene, dichloroacetic acid, trichloroacetic acid), air pollutants (particulate matter, black carbon, benzene), and endocrine-disrupting/reproductive toxicants (diethylstilbestrol, bisphenol A, persistent organic pollutants, dioxin). “ Epigenetics and environmental chemicals https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3035853/ These are some young people who have died this year of Cancer so far. 1. column31: A lot of people are now wearing masks when they are out in public, and they have even become required in some areas. With that in mind, we wanted to share some safety guidelines for wearing masks. 1. Wash Masks Often -- If your mask *is* washable (not all are). Wash on hot and dry hot as well, to kill germs. 2. Make Sure Mask Fits Properly -- It should cover both your nose and mouth and should fit tightly to your face. It shouldn't be open at the sides or bottom. 3. No Masks for Young Children -- We have seen people putting masks on infants and very young children. Don't do this! The masks, especially filtered, make it hard for even adults to breathe. This could actually suffocate an infant. Wear your baby instead, or leave your young children at home, if possible. 4. Wash Your Hands After Removing Mask -- Your mask may have become contaminated while out, so once it is removed (carefully!), place it in a safe location or storage container, and wash your hands before touching your face. 5. Avoid Masks While Driving -- There is no need to wear a mask while alone in your car, and at least one person has crashed from lack of oxygen. Put your mask on once you have parked and are ready to exit, but don't wear while driving. 6. Avoid Masks While Exercising -- You have an increased need for oxygen while exercising, and a mask can make it difficult to get the air you need. Skip the mask and exercise in an open area, away from other people (or exercise at home). 7. Remove Mask if you Feel Light-Headed -- Your safety matters, and if you're not breathing well or feel like you're going to pass out, remove your mask and breathe. Someone having to resuscitate you and touch your mask is worse than you removing it yourself so that you don't faint. Be smart. Be safe. If you choose to wear a mask, do it properly and only when you must.

column31: In honor of Earth Day, we're talking about the harms of pollution, specifically PM2.5. This morning we shared about the health risks of this pollution (check for that post if you missed it). Here are some of the sources of it. To some extent, we can't avoid PM2.5. Wood-burning stoves will produce it, and bonfires, and some people obviously need those. Right now, about half of our exposure to this pollution comes from things in the environment -- vehicle and factory emissions, burning of solid fuels, building materials. But about half also comes from petroleum-based fragrances. Yes, your scented laundry and dish detergents, air fresheners, candles, cleaning sprays, etc. are TOXIC! (They are also, usually, endocrine disruptors, messing up hormone balance.) Next up...how to reduce our exposure to PM2.5 pollution. Sources: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6156628/ https://science.sciencemag.org/content/359/6377/760 http://csef.usc.edu/History/2016/Projects/J2002.pdf

column31: How can we be sure the rush to create a coronavirus vaccine will not produce another disaster like the dengue vaccine? Despite billions of dollars of investment, efforts to develop safe and effective vaccines for dengue and similar viruses have repeatedly run into a major stumbling block called “disease enhancement”—meaning that the vaccine causes harm rather than offering protection. The Dengvaxia vaccine led to tragic injuries and 600+ deaths (as of Oct. 2019) in the Philippines, resulting in lawsuits. Their mass dengue vaccination program—implemented with undue haste—not only killed children but provoked protests, criminal investigations, indictments, revocation of the vaccine’s license and a plummeting of parental confidence in vaccine safety from 82% to 21% in the Philippines. Afterwards, the FDA still licensed it in the U.S. Sign up for free updates: ChildrensHealthDefense.org/sign-up:=:https://childrenshealthdefense.org/about-us/sign-up/

column31: In Idaho, a mother is arrested for letting her kids play on the playground. There are no signs that the playground is closed. No laws or orders in place that they are. A city official shows up and declares the playground "private property" and says he has the right to close them at any time for any reason, and demands everyone get off. When the mother asks questions and says this doesn't make sense to her, they arrest her. Right in front of her children and everyone else. (After the arresting officer shoves a young girl holding her baby sister.) There were many other ways the officers could have handled this. The mom is allowed to ask questions. If the officers can't deal with being questioned and help diffuse situations without ultimatums and quick arrests, they shouldn't be police officers at all.

It was the first battle in the war that has consumed my life — the struggle to confront politically powerful corporations that pollute our waterways and air, extinguish our wildlife, trample our purple mountain’s majesty, privatize the public commons and subvert our democracy. My goal is steadfast — to insure every American child the same opportunities for good health, dignity, spiritual enrichment and prosperity as our parents gave us. Pollution enriches billionaires by impoverished the rest of us. Our Creator speaks to us through the scriptures, the prophets, wise people and through art, literature, music and poetry — but nowhere with such clarity, texture, beauty, grace and joy as through Creation. When we destroy nature, we diminish our capacity to sense the divine — to understand our potential and our duties as children of God. Today, I give thanks to God for the land and water and for 350 courageous Waterkeepers around the globe who have pledged their lives to safeguarding our rivers and who recognize, as the scriptures teach us, that pollution is crime: “The earth mourns and withers, The world pines and fades, Both Heaven and Earth languish. The Land lies polluted, Defiled by its inhabitants, Who have transgressed the laws, Violated the ordinances, And broken the covenant, Therefore a curse consumes the land and its people burn for their guilt.” — Isaiah, 24:5 @waterkeeperalliance

column31: What is PM2.5? PM2.5 stands for "Particular Matter under 2.5 microns." That means very fine air particles that are easily breathed in and which can cause some serious health effects. PM2.5 is a significant source of pollution in our environment right now. Most of the effects are on the heart and lungs, because the particles are breathed in and irritate the lungs, and make it harder for the body to get properly oxygenated. This affects people of all ages, and long-term exposure is the worst, although short-term exposure can be dangerous too. PM2.5 pollution causes around 9 million deaths worldwide every year, making it one of the top health risks. There is no safe level of PM2.5 in the environment, although levels of less than 12 ug/m3 is considered to be the "safest." (But exposures even at 8 - 9 increased the risk of death from COVID-19 in a recent study out of Harvard.) Tonight we'll share the common sources of PM2.5, so don't miss that! This is the second in our "Improve the Earth!" series. Have you taken the pledge yet? Sources: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/31339350 https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/30181279 https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5689473/ https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17886048 https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27152932 https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16675438 https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1240126/ https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6613786/ https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11356-019-05825-4:=:http://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11356-019-05825-4

(In fact, according to a recent Harvard study, long-term exposure to this pollution increased the risk of death from coronavirus.) We want to make a big difference in everyone's health, and we can do this together. column31: It's Earth Day! And not just any Earth Day...but the 50th anniversary! Some fun facts about Earth Day: It was started by Senator Gaylord Nelson, who had been trying to get an environmental movement "officially" going since1963. It led to the creation of the EPA, as well as The Clean Air, Clean Water and Endangered Species Acts. In 1969, almost no one said the environment was a major issue...by by 1971 (the second Earth Day), 25% of people said it was important. In 1990, Earth Day became a world-wide celebration, named "Mother Earth Day" and celebrated in 193 countries. We're proud to be celebrating Earth Day today, and everyday! And we're excited to extend that celebration to all of you. :)

column31: We have BIG news! As a company, taking care of the Earth (and the people on it!) are very important to us. We use plants, nature's creation, to support our health...and we think nature deserves some support of its own. That's why we're excited to announce that, as of 2020, Earthley is going carbon-neutral! What does that mean? Well, in order to get our products into the hands of all our customers, we have to ship them. That means trucks and planes, which create carbon emissions. We're offsetting all of those emissions by donating to charities that plant trees to absorb them and help return the planet to a healthier state. In the first three months, this amounted to 63,000 tons of CO2 emissions...and we planted 1619 trees! We're so excited by where our mission is taking us, that we'll be celebrating with all of you on Earth Day, which is this Wednesday. Look for another special announcement, coming soon! :)

column31: On April 9, the FDA sent warning letters to a bunch of different companies, telling them to stop using the term "coronavirus" (or variations thereof) in conjunction with products, because this made it an "unapproved drug" and therefore was not allowed. Earthley was one of those companies. We had shared two groups of products that mentioned "coronavirus." One was intended for immune support, and one for helping with symptoms. Both of those are legal claims to make, but since we included the term "coronavirus" and the FDA is nervous right now, they said we could not do that. (Even though we NEVER claimed that any product could "treat" or "cure" coronavirus or anything else, because we know those are not legal claims.) They demanded a response from us within 48 hours, and told us they would be permanently publishing the letter they sent us on their site either way. (There is NO recourse to get this letter removed.) Although we responded -- and removed the word "coronavirus" from all listings -- within about 6 hours, they still have yet to update their site and show that we have taken corrective action and are in compliance. So the moral of the story is...the FDA is draconian and ridiculous.

column31: "The science is settled" has become a frequent mantra among certain groups of the last several years. They think they sound intelligent and forward-thinking, but they don't. Experiencing this recent pandemic, and watching the response to it has shown us that science is NOT settled...at all. We're constantly asking new questions, looking at new data, trying to make the best decisions we can with what we know (or believe we know). When we don't update our knowledge based new data and ideas, we make poor decisions. We should remember this is true in ALL areas. Science is never settled. We must always be asking more questions, doing new studies, examining and accepting new data. It's the only way to be sure that what we're doing is really the right way. Finally, we must remember what science *is*: a method of inquiry. It's a process for learning about the world around us. It's not a set of facts that never change, or a belief system. Anyone who claims "the science is settled" doesn't actually understand science at all.

column31: "Professor Ian Frazer, the immunologist who co-invented the human papilloma virus (HPV) vaccine which prevents cervical cancer, said a coronavirus vaccine was “tricky”. He said that although 100 different teams around the world were testing for vaccines, medical scientists did not have a model of how to attack the virus. The professor of medicine at Queensland University, which is testing for its own COVID-19 vaccine, said immunisation against coronavirus was similar to immunising against the common cold. “It is tricky, vaccines for upper respiratory tract diseases, because the virus lands on the outside of you,” Prof Frazer said. “The wrong vaccine could make things worse so we have to be very selective about what part of the virus we want to attack. “Coronavirus doesn’t get into you, it stays on the surface cells in your lungs. All these flu viruses get into you, so the body can fight and makes T cells. “This virus doesn’t kill the cells, it makes them sick. At the moment we don’t know how to make a coronavirus vaccine work. “That’s why there are 100 vaccines under testing using every conceivable approach. “We don’t know if any of them will work.” He said for 99 per cent of people who got coronavirus it was a trivial illness, but that was not the case for those in the vulnerable categories.” https://www.news.com.au/lifestyle/health/health-problems/no-vaccine-for-coronavirus-a-possibility/news-story/34e678ae205b50ea983cc64ab2943608 #covid #covid_19 #coronavirus #coronavaccine #covidvaccine #quarantine #billgates #covi̇d19 #corona

"Facebook will begin showing notifications to users who have interacted with posts that contain “harmful” coronavirus misinformation, the company announced on Thursday, in an aggressive new move to address the spread of false information about Covid-19. The new policy applies only to misinformation that Facebook considers likely to contribute to “imminent physical harm”, such as false claims about “cures” or statements that physical distancing is not effective. Facebook’s policy has been to remove those posts from the platform. Under the new policy, which will be rolled out in the coming weeks, users who liked, shared, commented or reacted with an emoji to such posts before they were deleted will see a message in their news feed directing them to a “myth busters” page maintained by the World Health Organization (WHO). “We want to connect people who may have interacted with harmful misinformation about the virus with the truth from authoritative sources in case they see or hear these claims again off of Facebook,” said Guy Rosen, Facebook’s vice-president of integrity, in a blogpost." Article ➜ https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2020/apr/16/coronavirus-facebook-misinformation-warning

column31: Many have seen some people in the pro-vaccine crowd crowing “See, anti-vaxxers! And this is the world without just ONE vaccine – you were wrong!” As odd and disordered as it is to be gleeful about a pandemic that’s sickening millions, their actual argument (such as it were) is still wrong in this case. A pandemic is nothing like an established illness, and the two cannot be compared. With an established illness, like chicken pox, most people in the population are immune to it at any given time. A small number will get it each year, a number that is very easy for society to cope with and care for. People tend to get it at a time when they’re at the most robust and able to easily handle the illness (not in infancy and not in adulthood, typically). We know the symptoms and how to help people through, including those who do have more serious symptoms. Then they, too, become immune. Their caregivers are also re-exposed and get a boost in their own natural immunity. This cycle of natural immunity from personal illness and for caring for one’s children and grandchildren during illness keeps the population generally safe. A pandemic is a different animal entirely. With a pandemic, it’s a completely novel strain of an illness that no one has immunity to. Every single person is vulnerable to it at once. No one knows how virulent it is, if it will mutate, how contagious it is, how to treat it, or anything else. Everyone is left scrambling. This can, and DID, happen in a world with vaccines. It’s the complete lack of knowledge that makes it potentially dangerous, and the fact that health care systems can become overloaded from lack of resources. Having vaccines doesn’t matter in this scenario, as we’ve all seen: it’s a completely new situation. Of course, vaccines actually are creating some problems with the cycle of natural immunity, too. Now, we’re seeing young mothers whose vaccine-induced immunity is not passing to their babies, leaving the babies vulnerable to illness at a time when they are more likely to struggle with it. We’re also seeing vaccines wearing off (or never working, but we don’t test people regularly to make sure their vaccines worked) in young adults, leaving them vulnerable to illness when it’s more dangerous for them, too. Heck – we’re even seeing cases where people are testing as “immune” via vaccine titers, and are *still* getting the illness! This shifting burden is real, and it is problematic. People who would have gotten mildly ill in middle childhood are now getting severely ill in infancy or adulthood. But let’s not deal with reality. Let’s, instead, become excited that a pandemic has shined a light on our extreme dependency on vaccines as the only viable solution to health. Is that the world you’re excited to live in – one with near-infinite ideas and options, that only focuses on one of them, dogmatically and ferociously? We're not.

column31: Lots of people are interested in using melatonin as a sleep supplement, because after all, it's "natural," right? But not so fast.... First, melatonin is a hormone (chemical messenger). If your body is not producing enough, then there's an underlying reason. Simply giving your body the hormone directly doesn't address that underlying issue. Second, the supplements that are on the market are *huge* doses. Studies that have been done on melatonin used much smaller doses (about 0.5 mg in adults), and focused on those with long-term sleep issues. Many people with mild or occasional sleep issues are using doses that are 10 - 20x higher, which is probably not appropriate! But we don't have the studies to know the long-term effects that has. We *do* know that even small doses raise the body's levels to much, much higher than normal levels. Third, side effects. Some people may have none, but several are possible. Fourth, a lot of the supplements on the market have a lot of 'extra' ingredients that are not at all healthy. The bottom line? Melatonin shouldn't be the go-to for sleep issues. It might have a place in serious or ongoing sleep issues, once other needs have been addressed (vitamin/mineral deficiencies and more), and in a very low dose. But for occasional sleeplessness, skip it. Sources: https://n.neurology.org/content/90/15_Supplement/P5.320 https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6419450/ https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26692007 https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3870602/

column31: There has been a lot of confusion about supplements lately. Some people have gotten the idea that "if a little is good, more must be better" when it comes to certain nutrients. Or, they've confused the amounts that are beneficial when not feeling well with amounts that should be used daily. Here's where we stand: for the most part, in most situations, mega-doses are bad. Every vitamin and mineral has an 'agonist' and an 'antagonist' in the body -- usually several. When someone takes a regular mega-dose of one nutrient, it causes the body to have high levels of that nutrient, PLUS all of the agonists. It causes deficiencies in all of the antagonists. For example, calcium and magnesium compete for absorption in the body. Take way too much calcium and it will lead to a magnesium deficiency. What we really need is balance. That's the holistic view. No nutrient is more important than another (generally speaking); we need all of them, in the right amounts, to be healthy. We trust nature, and our own instincts, for this balance. Healthy foods and herbs have what we need, in the right amounts. Mega-dose pills don't. (Ever notice that your pee turns bright yellow after taking a supplement? That's all the vitamins you didn't absorb.) Stick with nature. Naturally healthy and in balance. :)

column31: During pregnancy and birth, many women do not get informed choices. Since about 50% of women in the US now get Pitocin (synthetic oxytocin) at some point during labor, it's important to know the risks! The greatest risks with Pitocin are with women who are induced at or near term, when their bodies and babies aren't ready yet. In fact, Pitocin is *not* indicated for elective inductions. Risks can include a greater likelihood of c-section or use of epidurals (which come with their own risks). Fever is also a risk, which can lead to potentially unnecessary antibiotic use, destroying maternal and neonatal gut health and increasing potential resistance. Pitocin can also lead to hyperstimulation of the uterus, which can put the baby in distress, be extremely uncomfortable to the mother, or increase the risk of uterine rupture. High levels or long use of Pitocin can increase the risk of retained placenta, which can also increase the risk of both immediate and delayed postpartum hemorrhage. Once the baby is born, having had Pitocin affects the establishment of breastfeeding (and we know that when breastfeeding is established in the first few hours, moms are more likely to exclusively breastfeed for longer). There are minimal studies about the long-term effects on babies, but some suggest that motor development is negatively affected, even 5 years later. There is good news! When Pitocin use is minimal, is limited to cases where labor induction is truly needed, used after 39 weeks, or used to augment labor that is already established, the risks are lower. Preterm, elective, high-dose, or long-term use (long labor) increases the risks. Sources: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4982443/ https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/26011378 https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18342288 https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23571133 https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23181343 https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6494504/ https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3555986/ https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/31032882 https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6789409/ https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1586596/ https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/427052 https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/29523035 https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4410763/ https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/drugsatfda_docs/label/2007/018261s028lbl.pdf

column31: "According to the CDC, 2,841,600 people died in the US in 2019. That averages out to be 236,800 per month. Yet only 501,444 deaths have occurred nationwide this year between January 1, 2020, to April 9. Averaging the death rate over the first 3 months of 2019, there should have been 710,400 deaths, not merely 501,444, especially since the death rate for the flu is historically highest in January, February, and March. So, where are all the bodies from the 0.001242% deaths caused by COVID-19? In reality, we are experiencing a lower death rate in 2020 than in previous years. This lower death rate could be a mere coincidence, but historically the scientific data documents that when doctors go on strike, or simply don’t come to work, death rates drop significantly. In fact, no study has proven that death rates decline when doctors do come to work. The point being made here is, that when doctors are not performing elective, non-emergency procedures and interventions, (basically non-essential services) death rates historically drop. But as soon as doctors come back to work and non-essential services start up again, death rates increase. You might find it interesting that during this pandemic many doctors are being laid off. As mentioned earlier, many doctors are not working currently because their non-essential services are not needed, and this is the most probable reason that the death rate is only 70.59% of what it was in 2019 (5,116.76 per day instead of 7,248.98 per day) at this same time (April 9th.)” Excerpts from an interesting post by retired physician Dr. Tomas McFie: https://www.tommcfie.com/statistically-significant-why-it-makes-a-difference/ Article with links for reduced mortality rates during times of strike: https://www.psychologytoday.com/us/blog/slightly-blighty/201510/why-do-patients-stop-dying-when-doctors-go-strike #covid #covid_19 #coronavirus #pandemic #quarantine #covidnurses #coviddoctors #covi̇d19 #corona

column31: It being a holiday weekend, and a pandemic to boot, lots of women will get pressured to induce. Unfortunately, some of the most commonly given reasons are absolute nonsense. "Big Baby" -- Women can and do deliver babies that are 10 - 11 lbs. if they have support, their labors aren't rushed, and they can change positions as needed. Bigger babies may also be stronger and more able to 'help' with the birth. Plus, ultrasound readings are notoriously off, by up to 3 lbs. in either direction. A "big" baby may be a very average 7-lb. baby in the end. "Past due date" -- The range of normal gestational length is much longer than most realize. Doctors like to stick to right around 39 weeks, and some will go up to 41. But a few babies may need until 43 - 44 weeks! Plus, dates can be off. Even a first-trimester dating ultrasound can only date within 1 week, and women with longer cycles may not be as far along as they think, either. As long as baby is moving and doing well, there's no reason to induce. "Low fluid" -- Fluid pockets are very hard to measure once baby is near term, and doctors and ultrasound techs often miss one or more of them. True low fluid is VERY rare. Also, if mom rests and drinks plenty of water, fluid can be replenished. "Small/unproven pelvis" -- Very few women are 'too small' to be able to deliver their baby naturally, if they are able to move around as needed. And 'unproven' is just nonsense, everyone has a first time. A lot of these reasons can be avoided by choosing a care provider who isn't induction-happy and who doesn't push for a highly inaccurate, generally unnecessary third trimester ultrasound. As long as mama and baby are doing well, wait until baby is ready!

column31: These days, around 70% of women get epidurals when they're in labor, and that number has been increasing steadily for years. We've also seen a few hospitals currently *requiring* women to get them due to the pandemic! But do women really know what is in the epidural...or the potential risks they face? Regardless of what any woman chooses, she deserves full, complete informed choice. Most epidurals are a combination of two drugs: bupivacaine and fentanyl. The medication does cross the placenta and get to the baby, but the effects on babies aren't well-studied. Some old studies show that babies were a bit irritable or "difficult" in the first few days after birth, and that this affected bonding and maternal perception of motherhood, but there aren't more recent studies to confirm or deny this. Maternal risks are more clear. There's an increased risk of both instrument-assisted delivery and caesarean delivery. Plus, many women develop fevers, low blood pressure, dizziness, nausea, and may have slightly longer labors. Babies are more likely to be malpositioned. Of course, in some cases, moms can get exhausted or tense from pain, and an epidural might be what allows them to keep laboring and deliver successfully. There are different blends of pain medications and different amounts given, and lower levels of pain medications -- sometimes referred to as "walking epidurals" -- seem to have fewer risks for mom with good outcomes for mom and baby. If you are considering an epidural, ask questions about what kind of medication you would be given, the dose, and how much control you would have over it. Explore non-drug options as well. Sources: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25040829 https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4718011/ https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK279567/ https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3417963/ https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3106379/ https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25126704 https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4921713/ https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/7238154 https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4335561/ https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5136389/

Allowing these companies to focus the debate on COVID-19 has given them pretext to censor discussion of 5G and to shift the debate to a battlefield where the science is hypothetical and weak. We therefore urge health advocates to focus discussion on proven harms. There is ample pervasive human evidence of 5G and wireless harms. CHD’s work, including our historic lawsuit against the FCC for its false and obsolete health guidelines, is a potent threat to the wireless industry and its fraud on the public. CHD will continue to share the evidence and truth about 5G and wireless harms.

column31: Trying to keep your family healthy right now? We get it! Here are some of the best things you can do to stay well. Wash your hands -- This is the single most important thing. Wash your hands every few hours, after using the bathroom, before eating, and any time you have been away from home. Use regular soap and water (not antibacterial, which can negatively impact gut flora). If you can't wash, especially after touching door handles, payment kiosks, and other high-touch spaces in public, use a hand sanitizer where the active ingredient is 60% ethanol or higher. Don't touch your face! -- It's a habit for many, but if you touch a contaminated surface then touch your face, you're more likely to get sick. Avoid touching for any reason if you are in public, until you can wash your hands. (Even if you wear gloves...don't touch!) Stay home if you're sick! -- Symptomatic people are the primary ones who spread illness. If you have a fever, vomiting, or diarrhea, just stay in. If you are coughing heavily, stay in. Avoid crowds. If you MUST go out, consider wearing a mask and wash your hands immediately before you leave your home. Symptoms need to be gone for at least 24 hours **without** any type of medication before it's safe to venture out. Eat healthy -- Shore up your immune system by making sure you are getting plenty of fresh foods and all the necessary nutrients. Some nutrient deficiencies can increase your risk of getting sick (like vitamin C, D, and zinc and selenium). Avoid sugar and pro-inflammatory foods, as they can lower your immune system. Exercise moderately -- A brisk walk, some jumping jacks, whatever you enjoy. 10 to 20 minutes per day is good for most, and don't overdo it especially if you're not used to regular exercise. Too much exercise can have the opposite effect. Stay well, friends!

column31: I love this article so much 🌼 🌸🌺. I love that people are waking up to what is happening behind the scenes. It doesn't mean that you obsess over negative things - it means that you care enough about yourself and the world around you to have knowledge. These are REAL impacts on this world, on every single level and staying informed is important. "Seven Silver Linings of the Plandemic" 🌈 A few weeks ago, as I was desperately looking for an upside to a national shutdown, a post about the Earth healing from pollution came my way. The world’s air was cleaner, the water was getting clearer. That was nice, I suppose. That was something to hold on to in such a crap situation. And then people finally started washing their hands for the first time in their lives, which was a miracle in itself, hopefully that habit will stay. Then homeschooling and homebirth came to the masses; both significant sub-movements of the health freedom and parental rights movement. As long as one has money to put food on the table, it’s lovely being home in the evening to go on a sunset walk and read books to your kids and tuck them into bed. I try to hold onto these thoughts because this shutdown has been more divisive—in my personal life and in this community of ours— than the 2016 election. I have felt friendships die. I have read accusations that I don't think I'll ever get over. But it’s been three weeks now and I’m happy to report that my relentless optimism has bounced back three-fold on this wild ride, and I want to give you all my seven major pandemic wins to bounce around in your brains while you wander from your pantry to the sofa and back to the pantry again. 1. The whole world is waking up to the corruption at the W.H.O. This massive pandemic win is only in the beginning stages of unfolding this week and I can’t wait to see where it goes. Today the President announced that the U.S. would be withholding funding from the W.H.O. because not only did their incompetence bungle the initial response to COVID-19, but they assisted China in covering it up while inexplicably praising China’s actions and alleged "transparency." Senator Graham echoed the same defunding message this afternoon and assured Americans that there would be no W.H.O. funding in the next Appropriations Committee hearing. Last year the U.S. gave a total of $500M to the W.H.O., so this is no small potatoes. For those of you who don’t know, leading up to 2017, the Gates Foundation and China rallied hard for an Ethiopian warlord named Tedros Adhanom to become the W.H.O. Director despite his crimes against humanity, and despite the fact he is not a medical doctor. He defers completely to China, going so far as nominating a fellow Zimbabwean warlord as a Goodwill Ambassador to the W.H.O. at China’s request, because the guy allowed China to rape Zimbabwe of its natural resources with impunity. Here is an absolutely outstanding roundup of this madman’s resume. Just recently a few U.S. Senators began calling for the W.H.O. Director's resignation, and tonight there is a republican resolution for defunding the W.H.O. until he resigns. The brightest part of this event isn’t whether or not we are directly impacted by any decisions of the W.H.O. Director, but more so that that our fellow Americans have had their dreams shattered and realized that the W.H.O. is not an unbiased nearly-Godly public health entity doing what’s best for all of mankind. 2. The N.I.H.’s Anthony Fauci has taken a hard tumble. In just 14 days, Dr. Anthony Fauci went from having his face featured on New York cupcakes to trending #3 on Twitter with #FireFauci. It’s been a beautiful ball of fire. He’s been sidelined at press conferences, he’s been contradicted, he can’t keep his story straight, and he’s pivoted 180-degrees on whether America will return to normal soon because his buddy Bill Gates, captain of Team Apocalypse, told him to. He has multi-million-dollar conflicts of interest at the N.I.H. and he’s telling us that there will be no picking up and continuing on until his new va((ine hits the market. The masses have watched day after day as he’s refused to endorse a 30-cent potential cure for COVID-19 and Americans have had enough. He’s standing by and letting people die while the world waits, and waits, and waits for his va((ine. Two days ago he almost started laughing when he said, “I hope we don’t have so many people infected that we actually have that herd immunity.” There was an inappropriately huge smile on his face when he said it. column31: As recently as a few days ago, they were predicting that coronavirus in Ohio would peak late April to mid-May, with 10,000 new cases per day at that peak. This was supposed to justify all of the shut-downs, which have cost tens of thousand jobs (Ohio is the #2 state for unemployment right now). The previous projections, if we "did nothing" were 62,000 cases per day, peaking on Mar. 22. On that date, we had around 250 new cases, even though the beginnings of "social distancing" and school closings had taken place only a week prior -- not long enough to have had any kind of serious impact. (And we're supposed to believe that it reduced cases by 28,400%.) Monday, after getting "massive amounts of new data" they revised their projections. They're expecting it to peak TOMORROW. With around 400 new cases per day. They expect to have plenty of resources to handle this. Ohio isn't the only state coming out with new models. Many states are revising their case and death rates down...by exponential amounts. Instead of tens of thousands dead...they're thinking maybe a couple hundred (per state). Their reaction to this? "Oops, we didn't know." No restrictions have been lifted. Some states have clamped down further very recently. Some, like California, literally have police everywhere, pulling people over for trying to drive to the store or for not wearing a mask. How can we ever trust them again, if they overreacted THIS massively? The graph below is the actual number of new cases per day in Ohio, vs. the projected new cases. Each day, the difference between the numbers grows...because we're looking at a linear curve when they were expecting an exponential one. Put simply, they were just wrong. They were absolutely wrong. What do you think should happen next? How should we hold our elected officials accountable for this?

column31: It feels like we’re in the middle of some YA dystopian novel, right? People are sick and dying. Quarantine & lock-down orders are in effect worldwide. Many have lost their jobs. Health care and other “essential” workers are on the front lines, risking their own health for the sake of others. Officials are making decisions that some support & others question. Media reports increase the sense of fear & trepidation among the populace. How long the crisis will last is unclear. The question for me (and for each of us really) is a simple one: how then will we live? What will my role be in this story? I could be a mercenary, preying on the vulnerable. I could be an extra—in one scene & gone the next. I could be a character who is just looking out for their own needs. But if I had to pick, I’d want to be a heroine. Not necessarily the one at the center of the story. ☺️ But one who is definitely on the right side—pulling for the sick, the discouraged. One who reaches out & makes a difference in one of the darkest moments of her time. One that does her best to act rightly, love mercy, and to walk humbly. I said “If I had to pick...” and, guess what, I DO get to pick. I will not at this time share all that I’m doing behind the scenes but I will tell you this: I will continue to communicate, to the best of my ability, clear, helpful information that you may live your best, healthiest life. 🤗 So now I pose the question to you: how then will YOU live? 🤔 P.S. This post is a snippet of a convo I had w/ a friend today. 🧡 P.P.S. Grab my “Get healthier w/o dieting” free pdf from my website holistichilda.com (link in bio). These tips are applicable anytime & are particularly pertinent today!

column31: Conclusion: "Wireless devices are harmful to human health. For now, wireless technologies must be avoided as much as possible." They further write: " People should be made aware that the EMR from using day to day cellular, Wi-Fi and Bluetooth devices are harmful to human health. The levels of radiation observed in most cases such as phone calls, internet browsing on laptops and smartphones, using wireless routers and hotspots, Bluetooth smartwatches and smartphones are unsafe when compared with radiation limits determined by medical bodies. According to the current medical literature, various adverse health effects from exposure to RF EMR have been well documented... New and innovative wired solutions which provide the same level of user-friendliness should be encouraged." Background: This is a review article about the science on this issue. It is important because it was published in the IEEE journal. The IEEE is the international organization of engineers. The current FCC obsolete guidelines are based on the IEEE recommended guidelines which are thermally based i.e., they are based on the false assumption that unless the radiation changes the temperature in tissue, it is not harmful. That may be good physics but it is bad biology. When the FCC wanted to adopt the IEEE guidelines, all the health agencies wrote letters objecting to the guidelines. Some of them criticized the use of engineers' recommendations for biological effects when they didn't even have one medical professional on the committee that developed the guidelines.

column31: I don’t want to just muddle through this crisis. I want to thrive. 🥰Don’t you? Here are my daily non-negotiables: 1️⃣ Make music - It is an act of defiance to sing. 🎶 It brings joy the spirit & anyone in the vicinity. Grab your guitar, harmonica, or kazoo. Or just sing at the top of your lungs. Your neighbors will thank you. (Mine did just yesterday. ☺️) 2️⃣ Meals - Prioritize them. Nourish yourself & your family w/ the best, most nutrient-dense food you can find. Start your day strong. It’s a bit of self-care & pampering that can help carry you thru the rough patches. My go-to? 🍳 & 🥓 3️⃣ Meditation. Prayer. Quiet time. I don’t care what you call it. Carve out time to be still, be grateful, & focus on what you want for the world. (Someone recently told me that they wonder if we are at this standstill right now b/c so many people were in essence so stressed & anxious they were praying for a break!) Let’s focus now on health & resilience, joy & peace. ✌️ 4️⃣ Movement - I overheard a neighbor saying he was using this time to catch up on Netflix series. Ooookaaay. But what if we got outside & moved our bodies a bit? Don’t you think that might lift our spirits a bit more? Dance. Play. Run. Jump. Just don’t sit there, watching a blue screen. 📺 Please. column31: Should you wear a mask to prevent the spread of coronavirus? The CDC is starting to recommend that everyone wear one, and a few areas are even requiring it. But what does the science say? If people are sick, or suspect they may be, first, they should stay home. If they absolutely cannot, then they really need to be wearing a properly-fitting N95 or similar mask to prevent spreading anything. If people are not sick, or don't think they are...this is where the recommendation gets tricky. So far, the CDC and others are saying "just cover your face." They are being very non-specific about how to do that. The majority of people will not take the time to do any research into types of fabrics, filters, particles sizes, etc. That means most will use scarves, bandanas, homemade masks made of basic cotton, and things like that. They will likely have them somewhat loose around their faces and will not have a proper fit. (Some areas are even recommending these items to be used as masks!) Masks used in this manner are all but useless. Most fabrics will allow particles smaller than 2500 nm through; viruses are around 100 nm. Several studies show that high levels of viral particles go through. And while the masks may theoretically slow them down, they can travel up to 40 ft unencumbered, so that 6-ft "social distance" probably still isn't sufficient. And loosely-worn masks probably won't even do that well. We're talking 97% failure rates here. In some studies, even surgical and N95 masks failed in health care settings, to prevent the spread of coronaviruses. These homemade masks, made and worn by people who have not done the research, surely will fail. We're afraid that people will think they are "safe" and change their behavior if they have masks, feeling like it's okay to go out in public both if they are (mildly) sick or if they don't think they are, and with poor mask use, will just end up spreading it more. Plus, some people are already using it as a social stigma. That is, if you don't wear a mask or promote mask wearing, that you are terrible and don't care about people and should be reported. Just another way to divide people...without looking at the science to see if it's really the best plan. People will be much better off to stay home while sick, and to wash their hands often. Coughing or sneezing into their elbow will also help (at least according to a Mythbusters episode!). So much of the general response to coronavirus has been a guess. They're grasping at straws. But where there IS science, we need to look at it, to make careful decisions. Here are the studies: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24229526 https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/20584862 https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27531371 https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1854994/

column31: Tips for restorative sleep ✅ Tips for staying “woke” ✅ There’s a time for both. Sleep is for the body & brain. Being “woke” is about the spirit. Both are important at this time. Sleep tips: 1️⃣ Get sunrise sun. I know it sounds crazy but it sets your circadian rhythm &, yes, will up your melatonin production. 2️⃣ Turn your WiFi off at night. Let your body really relax w/o the stressor of radiation. 3️⃣ No late night snacking. Making your digestive system work at night interferes w/ deep sleep. 4️⃣ Wear blueblockers. 😎 Our ancestors only had firelight after sundown. Blue light from our devices & household lights sends the message to our brains & bodies that it’s the middle of the day. No bueno. (I like @primalhacker glasses. Link in bio. Use the code “holistichilda” for a discount) Woke tips: 1️⃣ Don’t believe everything you hear or see whether it’s on the news, YouTube, on social media🙂 or touted by people in white coats--particularly if they are attempting to inculcate fear. Be especially skeptical if everyone is saying the same thing. 2️⃣ Always ask questions. Who stands to gain from this? Follow the money trail. Be willing to learn from those who think differently from you. What if they’re right & you’re wrong? Stay open & curious. 3️⃣ Be brave. When you dare to challenge the status quo, you will get pushback. When there is name calling & it gets personal, you just might be on to something. 4️⃣ Trust your gut. If everyone is going in one direction, feel free to go a different way. I’m not advocating being rebellious for rebellion’s sake but listen deeply to your heart & do what you know is right, regardless of how it may be perceived. If you follow all of my tips, you will sleep well & still be woke. ☺️ I may get pushback for this post. Good. It means I’m helping people to think critically. Not a bad place to start. 👍 P.S. I think Dr. Tom Cowan is starting to rub off on me. He has been called "Doubting Thomas." :) I’ve interviewed him a number of times & this last interview challenged all of my preconceived notions re. infectious viruses. 🤯 Listen to Wise Traditions podcast #235 “Understanding our Current Health Crisis” wherever you get your podcasts.

column31: It looks like changes may be coming to the Vaccine Injury Compensation Program. From the article: Under the change made by the Obama administration, petitioners no longer have to prove that an injection caused their shoulder injury. Instead, they simply need to document a previously healthy shoulder, the administration of a vaccine in that arm, and the onset within 48 hours of shoulder pain that persisted for at least 6 months. If the U.S. government wants to deny compensation, it has to prove that the injury was not caused by the vaccine. Now, HHS under Trump is arguing that because shoulder injuries are caused by incorrect administration—a needle injected too high on the arm so that it penetrates the shoulder joint rather than the arm muscle—they should be jettisoned from the government-sanctioned list of injuries for which petitioners don’t have to prove causation. Instead, HHS argues, people with SIRVA claims should sue vaccinemakers and administrators in the civil courts (an outcome the 1986 act was intended to prevent.)

column31: We just want to warn our friends -- at this point, when the lock down ends, things do not go back to normal. We will have to go through several stages to try to find our "new normal" and that may take many months. Families who are lower-income will be hit hardest by this, sadly. First, people have to believe it's safe. Fear has been pounded into their heads for several weeks. Officials will tell them that the lock down can start again at any time if/when cases start to jump up again. They won't believe, right away, that things are really "okay." And they will probably remain suspicious of others, especially if they see anyone cough. Communication will be disrupted and people will be at odds. Second, people have to figure out their job situation. Do they still have one to go to? If not, are they able to get one? Many small and medium businesses will have gone under, so fewer jobs will be available. There will be a shift to people working for fewer larger companies, or for themselves/as contractors (such as Uber or Instacart type businesses). It will take a lot of people time to sort this out and find some kind of means of providing for themselves. Third, some things will have permanently shifted. For example, many people prefer staying home and ordering movies on their large TVs to paying to go to a theater. Maybe, now that theaters have been closed for several weeks, they will not go back to that, and new movies will just be released directly for streaming. This further disrupts businesses and jobs. Fourth, there will be a huge struggle between the people who want more laws and more promises to "prevent" something like this from happening in the future, and people who are angry that our rights were violated so heavily this time around. Some will push for 'immunity cards' (as Bill Gates has spoken of), requiring people to carry papers proving they are vaccinated or naturally immune to certain diseases in order to travel. They may push for immediate lock downs at the first sign of any disease outbreak. They may ask to ban children from public spaces. Some of these things are already happening. (See Costco and Menard's new policies, and the response to them.) On the other hand, some will demand that government officials get recalled and removed from office. They will demand provisions in the law that state that our rights cannot be superseded by illness or fear of illness. Depending on how vehement each side is, a civil war is not out of the realm of possibility (though we hope it doesn't come to that). Fifth, a lot of people will be massively in debt, some will have lost their homes, the food and supply chains will have been seriously interrupted. (They're already predicting a food shortage due to not enough workers to plant this spring.) It will take months or years to sort all that out and get back on track. So the end to a lock down is not the end. It will take at least months longer to find some new semblance of normal. The longer it goes on, the worse the after effects will be. This will permanently change the world.

column31: If you are expecting, and you are a low-risk mama, you may want to consider a home birth -- even if you wouldn't have under other circumstances. Why? Well... 1. Illness is circulating in the hospitals -- Sick people go there. Ventilation/air circulation means germs can get into other places. Poor hygiene of gowns and curtains can mean spreading illness, too. No one wants to get sick, or have their newborn get sick. 2. Moms being denied support people -- Some hospitals are telling moms they can't have their husbands/partners or doulas present during birth. This is extremely stressful for a laboring mother, and can result in stalled labor and a cascade of interventions. 3. Moms and babies being separated -- Some hospitals have enacted policies that if mom has, or is suspected to have, coronavirus at the time of delivery, they will be separated from their newborn for up to 2 weeks. This is a recipe for interrupted bonding, struggle to breastfeed, and PPD in mom. 4. Interventions pushed -- Now more than ever, hospitals don't have time to argue and believe that interventions like Hep B, vitamin K, eye ointment, etc. are "necessary" and they will force parents into it. They do this anyway, but they will insist and bully when under stress already. 5. Moms' rights respected at home -- Enjoy laboring at your own pace, with the support people you choose, followed by relaxing in your own bed with your new baby. No one pushed anything on you that you don't want. Trained support people will even clean up after, and are able to handle most situations that may come up (outside of true emergencies, which are rare). 6. Non-emergency appointments canceled -- Even if you have your baby in a hospital, most follow-up appointments are canceled. For continuity of care (and ease), midwives will come and visit you and baby at home to make sure you're doing well. Don't worry! Many experienced mamas, midwives, and doulas are stepping up to answer questions and help mamas who are just considering home birth to feel more comfortable. If you have questions, please feel free to ask!

column31: Giving birth is one of the biggest, most overwhelming things a woman will ever go through. Her physical and mental health are important, and yet, they're often ignored. When women experience a traumatic birth, where their wishes are ignored and they are unsupported, they are often told, "At least you have a healthy baby. That's what matters." This is dismissive and rude. Yes, of course a healthy baby matters. But it's not ALL that matters. A woman's physical, mental, and emotional health matter, too. Besides, do we really want the bar to be "mom and baby didn't die?" Just because both are going home in a few days and have no major, immediate issues doesn't mean baby won't struggle with gut health, successful breastfeeding, or colic. It doesn't mean mom won't struggle with PPD, pelvic floor dysfunction, or painful physical recovery. So please, stop saying this. Take women seriously. Listen to their stories. Respect their wishes and desires and stop pretending they are selfish for having them. Women deserve support and understanding and true bodily autonomy.

This also ensured that the proper process to set venue is used: a Multi-Jurisdictional panel lottery process (rather than the FCC) should now decide which court will hear CHD’s & EHT’s cases. The 4/1/20 publication means the two review petitions will soon be able to move forward to consideration on the merits. To support our efforts and ensure that we continue and do such excellent work on this case, please make a donation by choosing "Stop 5G" from the funding options here: https://childrenshealthdefense.org/about-us/donate/

column31: ✖️ New Study ✖️ While the whole world is captivated by #covid_19 a study was just published 2 weeks ago that found Autism Rates DECREASING among wealthy, educated Californians, and INCREASING among families living in poorer counties. The authors write: “There is an urgent need to understand what wealthy California parents are doing or have access to that may be lowering their children’s risk.” “There is an equally urgent need to understand the factors that may lead to increased risk of ASD among lower income populations, including factors that may be beyond their control, such as access to and autonomy over healthy food, health care, stressful environments and toxic exposures." "Rather than supporting genetic explanations, the DDS (California Department of Developmental Services) data tend to implicate environmental factors as underlying the etiology of ASD. For example, the lower prevalence of ASD in wealthy counties like Santa Clara from 2000 to 2013 could be explained at least in part by deliberate choices made by wealthy white and Asian parents, combined with wider access to better life options afforded to those with higher income and education. These choices may include prenatal and postnatal practices that prevent ASD from developing in the first place." This study refutes a purely genetic hypothesis, and points to ENVIRONMENTAL factors that wealthier parents are either AVOIDING or reducing risk, i.e. Tylenol, vaccines, artificial infant formula, antibiotics, etc. "California Autism Prevalence by County and Race/Ethnicity: Declining Trends Among Wealthy Whites” https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s10803-020-04460-0:=:https://idp.springer.com/authorize?response_type=cookie&client_id=springerlink&redirect_uri=https%3A%2F%2Flink.springer.com%2Farticle%2F10.1007%2Fs10803-020-04460-0 #autism #autismawareness #covid #coronavirus #pandemic #epidemic #asd #autismmom #autismfamily #autismspeaks #autismspectrumdisorder #tylenol #breastfeeding #vaccines #inflammation #publichealth
